        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Quick example of overriding `vim.paste`. May not be perfect.\n```lua\nlocal paste_lines = { '' }\nlocal is_normal_mode_paste = false\n\nlocal function exec_lines(lines)\n  is_normal_mode_paste = false\n  for _, line in\n    ipairs(vim.tbl_filter(function(v)\n      return vim.trim(v) ~= ''\n    end, lines))\n  do\n    vim.cmd('norm ' .. line)\n  end\nend\n\nvim.paste = (function(overridden)\n  return function(lines, phase)\n    if vim.fn.mode() ~= 'n' and not is_normal_mode_paste then\n      return overridden(lines, phase)\n    end\n\n    is_normal_mode_paste = true\n    if phase == -1 then\n      exec_lines(lines)\n    elseif phase == 1 then\n      paste_lines = { '' }\n    elseif phase == 2 then\n      paste_lines[#paste_lines] = paste_lines[#paste_lines] .. lines[1]\n      for i = 2, #lines do\n        table.insert(paste_lines, lines[i])\n      end\n    elseif phase == 3 then\n      exec_lines(paste_lines)\n    end\n  end\nend)(vim.paste)\n```\n\nNote that you could also use a key remapping to achieve the same effect. That way you could also use normal mode paste to paste text. This is also easier to set up.\n```lua\nvim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>np', function()\n  local cliptext = vim.fn.getreg('+')\n  for _, line in\n    ipairs(vim.tbl_filter(function(v)\n      return vim.trim(v) ~= ''\n    end, vim.split(cliptext, '\\n')))\n  do\n    vim.cmd('norm ' .. line)\n  end\nend)\n```",
